external_knowledge:
- 'High' risk is defined as projects with at least one bug;
- 'Low' risk is defined as projects with no bugs;
- The risk level is a simplified metric to help prioritize project management and quality assurance efforts.

- "blossomed with revisions" refers to projects that have had multiple revisions;
- "grappling with open bugs" refers to projects that have unresolved bugs;
- "most growth" refers to the highest number of revisions;
- "least challenges" refers to the lowest number of open bugs.

- "Seeds of code" refer to files that were initially created;
- "Towering trees" represent files with more than 100 lines;
- "Tended to more than once" means files that have been modified more than once.

- "Active files" are files that are currently in use and not archived or deleted;
- "Non-merge commits" are changes that do not result from merging branches;
- The net change in lines is calculated by subtracting the total lines removed from the total lines added.

- "blossomed with the most new lines of code" refers to files with the highest total lines added;
- "healing touch of bug fixes" refers to files that have had at least one bug fix;
- "how much have they grown and healed" refers to the total lines added and total bug fixes.

- "Flowers" represent changes in the project;
- "Gardener" represents the entity that introduces or fixes bugs;
- "Marks" represent bug descriptions;
- "Notes" represent comments on the changes.

- "vibrant garden of code" refers to a project with many active files and revisions;
- "flowers" are files within the project;
- "bloomed" refers to the number of revisions made to a file;
- "grown" refers to the number of lines added in revisions.

- 'Flowers' refers to file types in a code repository;
- 'Gardeners' refers to developers who make revisions;
- 'Watered' refers to making revisions to the files;
- 'Within the last two years' refers to the date range from January 1, 2022, to December 31, 2023.

- "New flowers" represent `lines_added` in the revisions;
- "Withered ones" represent `lines_removed` in the revisions;
- Each project is treated as a garden, and the files and revisions within it are the plants and their growth stages, respectively.

- "garden of project 1" refers to the set of files associated with project 1;
- "most influential developer" is the developer with the highest total impact score from their revisions;
- "weight of their contributions" is measured by the sum of the impact scores of the revisions they made.

- 'high-priority projects' are projects with a priority level of 'high';
- 'active projects' are projects with a status of 'active';
- 'active files' are files where the `is_active` flag is set to 1.

- "lines planted" refers to lines of code added in revisions;
- "lines removed" refers to lines of code removed in revisions;
- "weeds (bugs) uprooted" refers to the unique bugs fixed by changes;
- "notes (comments) left by gardeners (developers)" refers to comments made on revisions by users;
- "as the garden has grown over time" implies the cumulative impact of changes over the project's lifetime.
